==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Chen, Jian (2020): {{liushu|p}} of a woman wearing a feathered ornament on her head – original form of {{och-l|纛|feathered ornament}}. Later borrowed for {{och-l|毒|poison}}. If this is the correct interpretation, see also {{zh-l|*每}}.

Alternatively, Li Xueqin (2012) proposes it is a {{Han compound|屮|毐|c1=s|c2=p|t1=vegetation|ls=psc|nocap=y}}, meaning "a type of poisonous plant."

===Etymology===
; “poison”
: From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*duk ~ tuk||poison; to poison}}. Cognate with {{cog|bo|དུག||poison; toxin}}, {{m|bo|གདུག}}, {{m|bo|གདུག་པ||vicious; evil; poisonous}}, {{cog|my|တောက်||to suffer from toxicity; to be ill; to be poisonous}}.

; “to poison” (Pronunciation 2)
: A departing tone variant, meaning “to poison”, is preserved in southern varieties, including Cantonese, Hakka, Min, southern Gan, and southern Wu. It is derived from the sense “poison” with the ''*–s'' suffix in Old Chinese.

; “nerdy”
: Derived from {{zh-l|毒撚}}.

